USED DES TREE, FLAM SHEET, ABSORBED WITH LITTER, DMP WASTE, SENT REMAINING BACK TO SHIPPER.

DRIVER WAS INFORMED BY FOREMAN TANK WOULD HOLD PRODUCT.  TANK HAD ALARM AND GAUGE, AND FOREMAN WOULD BE WATCHING, BUT NEITHER WORKED.  DRIVER NOTICED PRODUCT WAS COMING OUT OF THEIR TANK AND SHUT OFF VALVES ON OUR TRAILER.  ORDERED NOT OVER 22,000 LBS.  WE LOADED 20,980 LBS.

A PAIL OF RESIN SOLUTION, A CLASS 3 LIQUID, WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKBLADE DURING HANDLING AT PRESTON'S PERRYOPOLIS SEVICE CENTER. THERE WAS SOME LEAKAGE FROM THE LID AREA OF THE PAIL. THE LID WAS TIGHTENED AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.
WHILE MAKING A LEFT TURN, HIT A PIECE OF STEEL PROTRUDING FROM A STATIONARY TANK, PUNCTURING THE TRAILER.

HAZ MAT IS SECURED WITH BOARDS; WHILE MAKING A RT TURN ONE V-BOARD FAILS ALLOWING ONE POLYDRUM OF HCL TO EXIT THE VEHICLE FROM THE LEFT REAR CORNOR OF THE TRAILER; DRIVER NOTIFIED DISPATCH VIA RADIO.  THE CORP. RESPONDS W/6 PERSONNEL TO SPILL SITE; DROPPED DM IS UPRIGHTED, AREA IS SECURED & ALL TRAFFIC IS DIVERTED AWAY FROM THE SITE, FIRE DEPT RESPONDS & INITATES A RINSE DOWN IN CONSTRUCTION W/HOLCHEMS'S PERSONNEL NEUTRALIZING SITE W/SODA DSH, AREA IS RINSED ONE MORE TIME; SPILL SITE IS REOPENED TO PUBLIC TRAFFIC.  PREVENTION OF FUTURE OCCURRENCE:  NO V-BOARD TRANSPORTATION OF DRUMS WILL BE PERMITTED BY ANY HOLCHEM VEHICLE -ONLY STAKES WILL BE ALLOWED FOR HAZ MAT TRANSPORTATION.

THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING SUPERVISORS WERE DRUMMING OFF INTO TOTES.  THE DRUMMING NOZZLE LEVER MALFUNCTIONED AND WOULDN'T SHUT OFF CAUSING AN OVERFLOW OF THE TOTE.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN VALVE AND STOPPED FLOW.  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF BY UNLOADING SUPERVISORS.

THIS SHIPMENT ORGINATED IN BOSTON MASS.  WAS LOADED AND SENT TO WHEELING WV FROM CARLISLE PA.   LEAKING WAS FOUND WHEN TRL. DOOR WAS OPENED AND DOCKMAN BEGAN TO UNLOAD MY FREIGHT.  LEAK WAS FROM A VERY SMALL HOLE IN THE LOWER 1/3 OF THE DRUM.  IT APPEARS THAT THE DRUM SUFFICED FROM METAL FATIGUE, CAUSING THE PIN SIZE HOLE.  2 ESTIMATE THAT NO MORE THAT A QUART OF PRODUCT LEAKED.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN A 55 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM, SPILLAGE WAS SOAKED WITH FLOORDRY, WHICH WAS PUT IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.  SPILLAGE ON THE FLOOR WAS NEUTRALIZED USING HORSEHOLD AMMONIA AND WATER PER BOB BEAKE OF MILES SAFETY DEPT.

ONE FIVE GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLE THAT WAS IN A CARDBOARD CARTON LEAKED BECAUSE THE LID WAS NOT TIGHT.  THE CARTON WAS REMOVED FROM THE PALLET AND OPENED.  THE LID ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS TIGHTENED AND THE BOTTLE WAS PLACED BACK IN THE CARTON WITH SAFETY ABSORBENT (CLAY).  THE CARTON WAS THEN PLACED IN DOUBLE PLASTIC BAGS AND SEALED WITH TAPE.  TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURANCES THE LIDS OF ALL BOTTLES SHOULD BE TIGHTENED BY THE SHIPPER BEFORE THE BOTTLES ARE PLACED IN THE CARTONS.  RETURN AUTHORIZATION WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

column168: FLEET TRANSPORT TANKER #351308 WAS BEING LOADED WITH CAUSTIC SODA.  WHEN THE LEVEL IN THE TANKER REACHED APPROX 3000 GALLONS, PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING FROM THE DISCHARGE PORT.  BOTH THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVES WERE CLOSED BUT LEAKING BY.  THE 3" CAMLOCK CAP HAD A HOLE IN IT AND WAS ALUMINUM AND DETERIORATED CONTINUALLY AS THE CAUSTIC PASSED THROUGH IT. ABOUT 5 GALLONS WAS LOST TO THE GROUND BY THE TIME THE LEAK WAS NOTICED. THE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND A BUCKET WAS USED TO CATCH THE LEAK WHILE PREPARATIONS WERE MADE TO TRANSFER THE LOAD TO ANOTHER TANKER.  WHEN THAT TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED, THE RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS INTRODUCED TO THE ELEMENTARY NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM AND THE INCIDENT WAS ENDED.

PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AN TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.  IN ADDITION, ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL BE REINSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER FOR ANY OBJECTS WHICH COULD DAMAGE THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF A CONTAINER PRIOR TO THE INITATION OF LOADING.

column168: A 5500 GALLON VERTICAL FARM FIELD STORAGE TANK WAS MOVED FROM A FARMER'S FIELD TO WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY.  THE TANK SHOULD HAVE BEEN EMPTY, BUT CONTAINED A SMALL RESIDUE.  THE TANK WAS TRANSPORTED ON ITS SIDE AND DURING TRANSPORTATION, SOME MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE FILL COVER.  THE STATE POLICE, HERIMSTON CITY POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED AND OVERSAW THE CLEANUP.  ABSORBANT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS THEN AGRONOMICALLY APPLIED TO AGRICULTURAL LAND ACCORDING TO THE EPA USE LABEL.  A REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF A HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE WAS NOT SPILLED.  HOWEVER, THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WAS NOTIFIED, RESPONSE NUMBER 281800, 281801, 281083, 281084.  THE OREGON STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND PROVIDED US WITH GUIDELINES FOR THE CLEANUP.  IN THE FUTURE, FARM FIELD STORAGE TANKS WILL BE CAREFULLY INSPECTED TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE EMPTY AND PURGED OF VAPOR TO REMOVE ANY POTENTIAL HAZARD PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

DRIVER WAS UNLOADING #2 DYED DIESEL FUEL.  HE WAS SUPPOSED TO PUMP IT INTO AN EMPTY TANK MARKED "REGULAR", HE INSTEAD PUMPED IT INTO AN 11,000 GALLON #2 DIESEL TANK THAT HAD 4,276 GALLONS OF CLEAR DIESEL IN IT.  HE DID NOT CHECK THE TANK GAUGE BEFORE UNLOADING.  DUE TO THE FACT THAT IT WAS DARK, WITH NO ARTIFICIAL LIGHT AND THE TANK WAS APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET AWAY FROM WHERE THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING, HE DID NOT KNOW HE HAD RUN THE TANK OVER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN A BERMED AREA.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS DUG UP AND DISPOSED OF UNDER SUPERVISION OF WYOMING DEQ.  DRIVERS ARE SUPPOSED TO GAUGE TANKS BEFORE AND AFTER DELIVERY.  I BELIVED IF THIS HAD BEEN DONE NO DIESEL WOULD HAVE BEEN SPILLED. ALSO BECAUSE HE WAS SUPPOSED TO PUMP DIESEL FUEL INTO A TANK MARKED "REGULAR GAS" ADDED TO THE CONFUSION.

ACFX 94638 WAS IN TRANSIT ON EXTRE GTW 5851 WEST, TRAIN 385 WHICH WAS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT.  ALTHOUGH THIS CAR WAS NOT DERAILED, NOR DID IT INCUR DAMAGE, HEAVY SLACK ACTION ACCRUED.  THIS ACTION CAUSED THE LADING TO SURGE AND SPEWED PRODUCT FROM THE AIR CONNECTION VALVE.  AN INDEPTH INSPECTION REVEALED THAT VALVE WAS OPEN AND PLUG WAS MISSING FROM VALVE CAP.  VALVE WAS CLOSED, VALVE CAP REPLACED, AND SITUATION WAS CORRECTED. CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  SHIPPER NEGLECTED TO PROPERLY SECURE CAR AT TIME OF LOADING.  THREE EMPLOYEES WERE EXAMINED AND TREATED AS OUTPATIENTS AT LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR ALLEGED EXPOSURE TO PHOSPHORIC ACID.  FURTHER MEDICAL EXAMINATIONS WERE CONDUCTED BY COMPANY PHYSICIANS.  ALL MEDICAL EXAMINATIONS AND TESTS WERE NEGATIVE.  EMPLOYEES LOST NO TIME FROM NORMAL ASSIGNMENTS DUE TO ALLEGED EXPOSURE.

THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE REPLACEMENT TRAILER AND THE LEAKING TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIR.

3/25/95 FORKLIFT DRIVER JOHN UNTEREINER, AT 1357, WAS TRANSFERRING 55 GAL DRUMS OF METHYLENEDIPHENYL DIISOCYANATE INTO MAUSK LINES 20 FOOT CONT #APMU276172. DOOR #75 IS WHERE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AND HAS A ONE INCH STEEL PLATE COVERING OVER THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR IN THIS AREA WHICH IS BORDERED BY A 3/8 INCH STEEL BORDER RIVETED TO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR. WHILE PROCEEDING TO LOAD THE DRUM INTO THE CONTAINER IT WAS NOT APPARENT TO ANYONE IN THE AREA THAT THE CORNERS OF THE STEEL BORDER WERE SLIGHTLY LIFTED, THEREFORE WHEN PROCEEDING FORWARD THE PATH OF THE DRIVER WAS IN LINE WITH THE LEFT CORNER OF THE STEEL BORDER. WHEN THE DRUM HIT THE STEEL CORNER IT WAS RUPTURED AT THE BOTTOM ON ITS SIDE, HOLE 2-3 INCHES IN DIAMETER CAUSING ENTIRE LOSS OF CONTENTS.

column168: AT ABOUT 1635 3/21/95, AN ADM TRANSPORT HAULING 7,800 GALLONS OF ETHANOL WAS ENROUTE TO THE AMOCO TERMINAL.  WHEN ENTERING THE TERMINAL, THE DRIVER TURNED TOO SHARPLY AND HIT A GUARD POST APPROXIMATELY FIVE FEET FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER DUAL WHEELS.  THE IMPACT RUPTURED THE TANK CAUSING A THREE FOOT OPENING IN THE LOWER HALF OF THE TRAILER.  ETHANOL SPILLED FROM THE TRAILER AND RAN DOWN THE DRIVEWAY INTO A DRAIN LEADING TO THE TERMINAL'S HOLDING POND.  BY 1700, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD ARRIVED AND DISPERSED FOAM ON THE SPILL TO SUPPRESS VAPORS.  BY 1730, ONE VACUUM TRUCK BEGAN PUMPING THE CONTAINMENT AREA WHILE A SECOND VACUUM TRUCK OFF LOADING THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE ETHANOL TRAILER.  BY 1900, THE VACUUM TRUCKS COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP AND BEGAN OFF LOADING THE ETHANOL/WATER/FOAM MIXTURE INTO THE TERMINAL'S HOLDING TANK.  ON 3/27, ADM TRANSPORTS ARRIVED TO BACKHAUL THE ETHANOL MIXTURE BUT EFFORTS FAILED DUE TO POOR WEATHER. ON 4/1, THE ETHANOL MIXTURE WAS SUCCESSFULLY TRANSPORTED TO ADM CORN PROCESSING PLANT IN DECATUR, IL FOR REPROCESSING.  TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS, ADM DRIVERS ARE INFORMED THAT GREATER CAUTION IS NECESSARY WHEN APPROACHING THIS TERMINAL ENTRANCE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 PM ON THURSDAY, MARCH 4, 1995 A BURSTING DISC ON AN MC338 CARGO TANK FAILED PREMATURELY WHILE THE TRAILER LEASED HYDROGEN IGNITED AT THE CARGO TANK VENT STACK CREATING A LASTED APPROXIMATELY ONE HOUR AND RESULTED IN EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DECIDING TO EVACUATE THE MANUFACTURING FACILITY AND A NEARBY BOWLING ALLEY.  ALTHOUGH THE BURSTING DISC FAILED PREMATURELY, THE RELEASE OF PRESSURE IS THE INTENDED RESULT. THE BURSTING DISC IS ONE OF TWO PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICES WHICH PROTECT THE CARGO TANK FROM OVERPRESSURIZATION.  THE BURSTING DISC FAILED AFTER THE TRAILER HAD BEEN PRESSURED TO TRANSFER PRODUCT INTO THE CUSTOMER TANK. THE DISC WAS RATED FOR 210 PSING BUT FAILED PREMATURELY AT APPROXIMATELY 145 PSIG.

TRAIN 556-01 TRAVELING SOUTH TO SARATOGA EXPERIENCED EMERGENCY BRAKE APPLICATION.  INSPECTION REVEALED A DERAILMENT HAD OCCURRED APPROXIMATEY 3 MILES NORTH OF PORT HENRY, NY (HEAD END OF TRAIN AT MP 119, REAR END AT MP 120.4).  TWENTY NINE CARS OF 90 CAR TRAIN DERAILED (9TH THROUGH 27TH CARS AND 42ND THROUGH 51ST CARS) DUE TO LESS THAN REQUIRED INNER COIL SPRINGS ON CAR BM5270 AT THE BL LOCATION ON THE SOUTHWEST SIDE, EXAGGERATED BY A WHEEL FLANGE HEIGHT DIFFERENTIAL ON THE L1 91-31/64) AND THE L2 (1-16/64) WHEEL COMBINED WITH A SUSPECTED DEVIATION IN CROSS-ELEVATION. WITHIN FRA SPECIFICATIONS, CAUSING THE L2 WHEEL TO LIFT AND SPREAD RAIL.  OF THE 29 CARS DERAILED, ONE HAZMAT, CAR CGLX 690, SODIUM CHLORATE, WAS DELIVERED ON THE WEST SIDE OF THE TRACKS PARTIALLY SUBMERGED IN A SMALL INLET OF WATER. SHIPPER/MANUFACTURER EKA NOBEL ADVISED RAILROAD NOT TO OPEN THE SODIUM CHLORATE CAR DUE TO THE SPILLED LUMBER AROUND CAR.  TESTING OF WATERS AROUND CAR AND IN LAKE CHAMPLAIN WAS BEGUN BY ADIRONDACK TESTING LABS (FOR DELAWARE AND HUDSON) AND C.T. MALE ENGINEER (FOR NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF CONSERVATION).  ALL TESTS HAVE BEEN NEGATIVE - NO PRODUCT DETECTED IN WATERS.  MARCH 5, 1995- UNDERWATER VIDEO DEPLOYED TO SEARCH FOR DAMAGE TO CAR AND PRODUCT IN WATERS.  NO OPENINGS DISCOVERED OR VISIBLE PRODUCT. MARCH 10, 1995- ALL LUMBER WAS REMOVED FROM AROUND THE SODIUM CHLORATE CAR.  MARCH 15, 1995 - HATCHES WERE OPENED ON CAR REVEALING THAT SUBMERGED COMPARTMENT HAD FILLED WITH WATER TO THE LEVEL OF THE POND AND WATER HAD FROZEN.  TESTS WERE TAKEN OF LAGOON, AREA AROUND CAR, LAKE AND IN THE SUBMERGED COMPARTMENT.  RESULTS OF TESTING INDICATED NO PRODUCT DETECTED IN ANY OF THESE AREAS. THE TOP COMPARTMENT OF CAR WAS FOUND TO BE INTACT, STABLE AND DRY.  THE PRODUCT IN THIS COMPARTMENT WAS NOT IN DANGER OF RELEASING.  MARCH 17, 1995- UNDERWATER INSPECTION REVEALED A LARGE RIP IN END OF CAR.  VISIBILITY AND DEBRIS FROM DERAILMENT DID NOT ALLOW FOR A THROUGH INSPECTION OF AREA.  AREA WAS NOT PREVIOUSY INSPECTED DUE TO LUMBER LYING AGAINST CAR.  NO PRODUCT WAS VISIBLE BELOW CAR OR AROUND HOLE.  LOW AREA OF LAGOON WAS ALSO INSPECTED AND NO PRODUCT NOTED.  TESTS WERE AGAIN PERFORMED BY ADIRONDACK TESTING LABS AND RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE. AGAIN, NYS DEC WAS PRESENT FOR ALL TESTING AND INSPECTIONS.  TWO TANK TRUCKS WERE SUPPLIED BY WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL TO TRANSLOAD SODIUM CHLORATE IN UPPER COMPARTMENT OF CAR.  LIQUIDIFIED AND PUMPED APPROXIMATELY 50% OF SODIUM CHLORATE IN UPPER COMPARTMENT FILING ON E OF THE TWO TANK TRUCKS.  DURING INITIAL PUMPING PROCESS A HOLE WAS DISCOVERED IN THE "B" END OF CAR.  HOE WAS 6" IN DIAMETER AND WAS PREVIOUSLY OBSCURED BY THE SODIUM CHLORATE FROM THE INSIDE AND BY THE RAILWAY EMBANKMENT ON THE OUTSIDE.  PUMPED PRODUCT TO A LEVEL BELOW THIS HOLE AND RETAINED THE LIQUIDIFIED SODIUM CHLORATE BELOW THIS HOLE.  NYS DEC, US EPA AND NYS DOT WERE PRESENT AND MADE AWARE OF THIS BREACH. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM STANDARD CHLORINE OF DE, INC. LOCATED AT 745 GOVERNOR LEA ROAD IN DELAWARE CITY, DE TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER STOPPED AT A SERVICE PLAZA LOCATED ON ROUTE 30 WEST IN BREEZEWOOD, PA TO CONDUCT A ROUTINE TIRE AND LOAD CHECK.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE LOAD, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE AND CONTACTED HIS HOME DISPATCHER WHO, IN TURN, DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SCENE, THE TRAILER WAS ENTERED AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PINHOLE LEAK HAD DEVELOPED RESIDUE LIQUID THAT WAS NOT EVIDENT AT THE TIME OF LOADING TO ESCAPE FROM THE PACKAGE.  THE CREW ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE CINCINNATI, OH IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM A DEFECTIVE SIDE BUNG CAP ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM. ALL CLEAN UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE STRUCTURALLY SOUND.

IN BLAINVILLE, QUEBEC TRANSPORTING CONTAINERS BEING SHIPPED BACK TO THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER (CLEAN HARBORS, CT). ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED IN THE CONTAINER AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM STABLEX CANADA, INC., ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 ON MARCH 16, 1995 AT HOBSON YARD IN LINCOLN, NEBRASKA, TANK CAR BN 974362, FUEL OIL, COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID NA1993,PG111, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BETWEEN THE MANWAY RING AND THE MANWAY COVER.  THE BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR FROM OMAHA, NEBRASKA RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND DISCOVERED THAT TANK CAR WAS OVERLOADED AND THAT THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS APPROXIMATELY THREE INCHES BELOW THE TOP OF THE MANWAY RING. AFTER APPROXIMATELY 900 GALLONS OF LADING WAS REMOVED FROM THE TANK CAR, IT WAS RELEASED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY OUR COMPANY FROM BABSON BROTHERS, MARCH 30, 1995, WITH A TOTAL OF SEVEN SCHEDULED DELIVERIES ON APRIL 1 ST AND 2ND. THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  1.  CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE), 8, UN1760, PG 11. 2.  CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE, SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE), 8, UN1760, PG11.  3.  CORROSIVE SOLIDS, N.O.S. (SODIUM HYDROXIDE), 8, UN1759, PG 11.  4.  CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (PHOSPHORIC & SULFURIC ACID), 8, UN1760, PG 11.  5.  HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION WITH MORE THAN 5 PERCENT BUT LESS THAN 16 PERCENT AVAILABLE CHLORINE CORROSIVE MATERIALS, 8, UN1791, PG 111.  ON MARCH 31, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 2100 A TRAILER CONTAINING THE AFOREMENTIONED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS GOING THROUGH OUR SAFETY LANE FOR INSPECTION AT OUR HENDERSON COLORADO TERMINAL FACILITY FOR A ROUTINE INSPECTION WHEN A LOOSE PLACARD HOLDER WAS DETECTED.  UPON DISCOVERY OF THE LOOSE PLACARD HOLDER THE TRAILER WAS ROUTED INTO THE SHIP IN ORDER TO HAVE THE PLACARD SECURED TO THE TRAILER WITH A RIVET.  A MECHANIC WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DRILLING A HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER WHEN HE DRILLED INTO THE SIDE TOO FAR PUNCTURING A THIRTY (30) GALLON DRUM CONTAINING CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (POTASSIUM HYDOXIDE, SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE), 8, UN1760, PG 11.  AFTER IT WAS DISCOVERED THE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED, THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO A REMOTE AREA OF THE TERMINAL FACILITY WHERE IT WAS SECURED AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED.  A SPILL RESPONSE FIRM WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED IN ORDER TO CLEAN UP THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE L.E.P.C. AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL, HOWEVER, DID NOT RESPOND TO THE SCENE SINCE THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED.  THE SPILL RESPONSE FIRM (WEST HAZ MAT) ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS AND WENT IN TO INVESTIGATE.  THEY LOCATED THE PUNCTURED DRUM AND PLACED IT INTO AN OVERPACK.  THE MATERIAL THAT HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND WAS SCRAPED UP AND PLACED IN A DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  THE REMAINDER OF THE FREIGHT WAS UNLOADED AND CLEANED OFF.  THE TRAILER WAS WASHED OUT AND THE MATERIAL WAS RE-LOADED.  THE MECHANIC WHO HAD DRILLED THE HOLE IN THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL, DUE TO SOME OF THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED ONTO HIS HAND.  THE MECHANICS HAND WAS CHECKED AND HE WAS RELEASED BY THE DOCTOR TO RETURN TO WORK.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED, A DECISION HAS BEEN MADE THAT A TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CANNOT BE WORKED ON WITHOUT PRIOR AUTHORIZATION FROM A SHOP SUPERVISOR.  EXTRA PRECAUTIONS WILL BE TAKEN WITH ANY TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CANNOT BE WORKED ON WITHOUT PRIOR AUTHORIZATION FROM A SHOP SUPERVISOR.  EXTRA PRECAUTIONS WILL BE TAKEN WITH ANY TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  ALL OF OUR EQUIPMENT IS MAINTAINED ON A REGULAR BASIS AND IS NOT UTILIZED UNTIL IT HAS BEEN PROPERLY MAINTAINED.  THE INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED IS AN ISOLATED INCIDENT AND TO MY KNOWLEDGE, NOTHING LIKE THIS HAS EVER OCCURR

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC.  LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVE IN BRAINTREE, MA TO ECOVA CORP. LOCATED ON HWY 71 - 5 MILES SOUTH OF KIMBALL IN KIMBALL, NE.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAPS OF 8 OF THE CONTAINERS ON THE LOAD AND SMALL PINHOLE LEAKS HAD DEVELOPED IN THE BOTTOM OF 4 OTHER CONTAINERS RELEASING A TOTAL OF 15 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT A TEMPERATURE CHANGE CAUSED THE MATERIAL INSIDE THE CONTAINERS TO EXPAND FORCING THE MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE CONTAINERS.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS INTO SUITABLE SALVAGE CONTAINERS. ALL CLEAN-UP RESIDUE WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUMS AND WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT. PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO OBSERVED.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND NOT TO BE PROPERLY CLOSED OR NOT STRUCTURALLY SOUND. column168: ADRIAN ARRIVED AT THE BULK PLANT.  HE AND PETE SET THE MANIFOLD VALVES TO BEGIN UNLOADING AND, AFTER DOUBLE CHECKING THE VALVES, ADRAIN BEGAN UNLOADING THE PREMIUM NO LEAD.  AS HE WAS UNLOADING, PETE WENT BACK INTO THE VALVE SHED AND CHANGED SOME OF THE VALVE SETTINGS, CAUSING THE PRODUCT ADRAIN WAS UNLOADING TO FLOW TO AN OLD, UNUSED AND OUT OF SERVICE-1000 GALLON TANK.  WHEN ADRAIN HAD PUMPED THE ESTIMATED 1059 GALLONS, THE 1000 GALLON TANK RUPTURED.  WHEN ADRAIN SAW WHAT WAS HAPPENING, HE REVERSED HIS PUMP AND BEGAN PULLING THE PRODUCT BACK OUT OF THE TANK AND INTO AN EMPTY COMPARTMENT ON THE TRAILER.  ADRIAN WAS ABLE TO RECOVER 619 GALLONS.  THE REMAINING 440 GALLONS LEAKED ONTO THE BULK PLANT PROPERTY.  THE GRANBY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED BY THE BULK PLANT.  THEY RESPONDED AND WERE UNABLE TO CLEAN UP AN ADDITIONAL 200 GALLONS OF GASOLINE AND WATER MIXTURE.  619 GALLONS OF PREMIUM NO LEAD GASOLINE WAS RECOVERED-UNDAMAGED. IT WAS PUMPED INTO PETE'S 66 DELIVERY TRUCK.  440 GALLONS OF PREMIUM NO LEAD WAS LOST AND /OR CONTAMINATED.  COST IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME. THE CLEAN-UP WILL BE THE RESPONSIBLITY OF PETE'S 66 SERVICE.  RICHARD STEWART CALLED WEST HAZ/MAT. THEY RESPONDED WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AND BACK HOE. WEST HAZ/MAT'S ON SCENE COORDINATOR WAS DAVE ELMER.  HE WAS INTRODUCED TO PETE'S 66 ON SCENE COORDINATOR BY RICHARD STEWART.  THAT WAS THE EXTENT OF BASIN WESTERN'S INVOLVEMENT IN THE CLEAN-UP.  ALL CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES WERE PLANNED AND ACCOMPLISHED BY WEST HAZMAT AND PETE'S 66 SERVICE.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: ALLEN BRUMFIELD CLIMBED TO THE TOP OF THE TRAILER TO HOOK UP THE AIR SUPPLY IN ORDER TO BEGIN OFF LOADING. THE PIPE FITTING THAT THE AIR SUPPLY CONNECTS TO WAS BROKE OFF AT THE THREADS - APPR. 6 INCHES ABOVE THE FLANGE CONNECTION TO THE TANK. THIS ALLOWED A 3/4 INCH OPEN PIPE TO THE VAPOR SPACE OF THE TANK. AT THAT POINT, ALLEN INSPECTED THE TRAILER TO SEE IF ANY ACID HAS SLOSHED OUT OF THE OPENING. THERE WAS A DETECTABLE TRACE OF MATERIAL ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK AND A FEW DROPS ON THE GROUND BENEATH THE TRAILER. THE PLANT (INEL) PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED BY ALLEN. THEY, THEN NOTIFIED THE IDAHO STATE POLICE WHO, IN TURN, BEGAN IDAHO'S EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS PLAN. OFFICER ANDERSON WITH THE IDAHO STATE POLICE INVESTIGATED THE INCIDENT. THE EMERGENCY PREPAREDNESS RESPONSE COMMITTEE DEEMED THE INCIDENT AS INSIGNIFICANT. AS PREVIOUSLY STATED THERE WAS NOT ANYTHING TO CLEAN-UP WAS NECESSARY. IN RESPONSE TO OUR INVESTIGATION INTO THE INCIDENT AND IT'S CAUSES, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS COMPLETELY UN-AVOIDABLE. WE WILL REPLACE THAT SECTION OF PIPE WITH STAINLESS STEEL IN ORDER TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

THIS LOAD WAS PICKED UP AT NEOSHO, MO. DRIVER SAID THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LIQUID IN LOAD. ON THE TRIP BACK, WATER CAME TO THE TOP OF THE LOAD. DRIVER WAS NOT AWARE OF IT BECAUSE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS TARPED. AS THE DRIVER WAS APPROACHING FARMINGTON RD. ON STERLING AVE., HE SLOWED TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN. THE LIQUID IN THE BOX SPILLED OVER ON THE BLACKTOP. OIL DRY WAS PUT ON THE SPILL AND SWEPT UP. THEN SAND WAS PUT DOWN AND SWEPT UP. ALL OIL DRY, SAND AND CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PUT IN ROLL-OFF BOX WHERE IT ORIGINATED. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE SLUDGE WATER CONTENT MUST BE LOWERED TO CORRECT THE LIQUID PROBLEM. ALSO, OUR DRIVERS WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO WATCH OUT FOR LOADS THAT HAVE A SPILLAGE PROBLEM. NATIONAL RESPONSE WAS NOTIFIED ON 3-11-95 AT 8:20 A.M. REPORT #282805 ILLINOIS EPA WAS NOTIFIED ON 3-11-95 AT 11 A.M. REPORT #950493 PEORIA COUNTY SHERIFF ON 3-11-95 AT 8:25 A.M. REPORT #952172.

column168: AT 1210 P.M. FRIDAY THE 3RD OF MARCH 1995 MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. JOHN LYON M.T.O. OGDEN REGARDING TANK CAR TGOX 30630 LOADED CAR OF METHYL TERT BUTYL ETHER, HE REPORTS THE CAR IS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. INSPECTION BY MGR. RODBOUGH REVEALED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND COULD NOT BE COMPLETELY CLOSED, AS THE OPERATING HANDLE (RATCHET TYPE) MALFUNCTIONED WHEN ENGAGED. THE OUTLET NOZZLE CAP WAS TIGHT BUT STILL ALLOWED THE CAR TO LEAK, INDICATING THE CAP COULD NOT BE REPLACED IF REMOVED BECAUSE OF THE QUANTITY OF THE LEAK. REPAIR WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY BACKING THE CAP OFF THE OUTLET NOZZLE EXTENSION, THEN APPLY GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL TO THE THREADS, THEN TIGHTENING THE CAP OVER THE TEMPORARY GASKET. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AND CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED MR. TOM FLORZ WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED INCIDENT #34075. MR.TYRONE SVEHLA CUSTOMER SERVICE SUPERVISOR FOR COASTAL CHEM AT WYCON WYOMING, (307-637-2700) ALSO FURNISHED WITH DETAILS, STATED THAT HE WOULD SEE THE CAR WAS SHOPPED FOR REPAIR.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A.LOW, DURING COMPLIANCE INSPECTION OF SOUTH FOUR TRACK, CHEYENNE, NOTED TANK CAR TGOX 21006, PHOSPHORIC ACID, LEAKING FROM TOP. INSPECTION FLANGE WERE LOOSE. MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A.LOW, TOOK 1/3RD TURN ON ALL FOUR NUTS, WHICH STOPPED LEAK. JOE RAZISON, CHEMTREC FILE #34052 AND RON VARNER, NU-WEST INDUSTRIES, WERE NOTIFIED OF EXCEPTIONS.

THE CREW OF THE UPRR LRA03-05 NOTICED A STRONG ODOR FROM THE CAR WHEN THEY ATTEMPTED TO MOVE THE CAR. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON THE AMPRO LEAD AND NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO UPRR MANAGER OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS TOM RICHARDS. RICHARDS IN TURN NOTIFIED UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON. ROBINSON TELEPHONED MR. MICHAEL SHAW, SHIFT SUPERVISOR FOR TRIAD CHEMICAL AT DONALDSONVILLE, LA. THE LOADERS OF THE CAR. SHAW STATED THAT HE WOULD RESPOND TO THE SCENE. ROBINSON AND RICHARDS ALSO RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND REMOVED SEAL "TRIAD 04300" FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING LID SECUREMENT PIN. ROBINSON WAS UNABLE TO DETECT ANY LEAKAGE OR DEFECTS. ROBINSON TELEPHONED SHAW AGAIN. SHAW ADVISED THAT HE HAD ALREADY INSPECTED THE CAR AND HAD FOUND THE "A" END LIQUID VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE. SHAW CLOSED THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED THE PLUG AND THIS SECURED THE CAR FROM LEAKING. SHAW FURTHER ADVISED THAT TRIAD WANTED THE CAR RETURNED TO THE DONALDSONVILLE PLANT FOR UNLOADING AND FURTHER INSPECTION. ROBINSON ADVISED RICHARDS WHO SAW THAT THIS REQUEST WAS CARRIED OUT. RICHARDS NOTIFIED THE DONALDSONVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE ASCENSION PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE AND ROBINSON NOTIFIED THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE.

column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY C. HILL RECEIVED PHONE CALL FROM SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE PHIL LUZMOORE ADVISING D.Q. & E. RAILROAD HAD REFUSED TANK CAR ACFX 94314 AT INTERCHANGE IN PERKINS, AR. DUE TO CAR LEAKING FROM MANWAY. MANAGER HILL RESPONDED, HIS INSPECTION REVEALED RUBBER MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS NOT ALIGNED PROPERLY ALLOWING LADING TO LEAK DOWN SIDE OF CAR. USED GASKET HAD BEEN CUT. REPLACED WITH NEW RUBBER GASKET. CHEMTREC'S JIM COOPER ASSIGNED REPORT NO. 34136 TO THIS INCIDENT SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE PHIL LUZMOORE WAS NOTIFIED OF REPAIRS.

FOR OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL AT (206-593-1316) WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS, STATED THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

WHILE CONDUCTING REGULATORY COMPLIANCE INSPECTIONS AT OGDEN UT. MGR. H.W. RODABOUGH INSPECTED TANKCAR MKT100407, LOADED TANKCAR OF DIESEL FUEL. NOTED PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, TO BE LOOSE ALLOWING THE CONTENTS, FUEL OIL TO SPILL FROM THE CAR. MGR. RODABOUGH REMOVED THE PACKING GLAND NUT AND APPLIED GORTEX GASKET MATERIAL, THEN RETURNED THE NUT AND TIGHTENED IT, THUS TERMINATING THE LEAKING CONDITION. NO REPORT WAS MADE TO CHEMTREC AS THIS WAS A MINOR CONDITION, THE SHIPPER AMOCO WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS, SUPERVISOR MAINTENANCE AND SERVICE STEVE DUVALL (801-539-7370) STATED THEY WOULD TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTION.

REEDER REMOVED SEAL 855482 FROM THE MANWAY. THE COVER GASKET WAS BROKEN IN TWO PLACES. REEDER FORMED A NEW GASKET FROM GORE-TEX AND RESEALED THE CAR WITH UP 483324. column168: WHILE THE DRIVER WAS FILLING OIL TANK THE HOSE RUPTURED CAUSING OIL TO ESCAPE.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

PRODUCT WAS DISPLAYED ON BOTH SIDES AND TOP OF TANK MANWAY AREA.  AN INSPECTION REVEALED THAT LIQUID EDUCATION LINE CAP WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND BOTTOM OF CAP.  THE TANK WAS DEPRESSURIZED AND LIQUID EDUCATION LINE CAP WAS REMOVED.  THE THREADING ON LIQUID EDUCATION LINE WAS WRAPPED WITH TEFLON TAPE AND CAP WAS PROPERLY TIGHTENED.  ALL PRODUCT WAS FLUSHED WITH COPIOUS STREAMS OF WATER FROM EXTERIOR OF TANK AND RUNOFF WAS NEUTRALIZED.  CAR CONTINUED ENROUTE WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  SHIPPER NOTIFIED TO PROPERLY SECURE CAR AT TIME OF LOADING.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE. DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE HOSE FITTING TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  WHILE UNLOADING, THE FITTING TIPPED SIDEWAYS ALLOWING GAS TO FLOW ONTO THE PARKING LOT.  SOME OF THE GAS ENTERED A STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN. THE TROY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND FLUSHED THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM. THE NEW YORK REPRESENTATIVE TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP.  THE NY STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION REFERENCE NUMBER FOR THIS INCIDENT IS 94-16112.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1445 HRS. ON MARCH 13, 1995, CM CARMAN SHINAVER AND COND. RUMPEL, WHILE PERFORMING AN AIR TEST ON TRAIN 771 IN DURAND, MICH. OBSERVED DRIPPING COMMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF CAR GATX43713.  THE CM DISPATCHER WAS NOTIFIED WHO IN TURN CONTACTED CHEMTREC.  CM SUPERINTENDENT R. ZIESEMER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  CARMAN SHINAVER WAS ADVISED TO PUT A PLASTIC BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK IF IT WAS SAFE TO DO.  CARMAN SHINAVER DID PLACE A BUCKET UNDER THE LEAK AND SECURED THE AREA.  CHEMTREC NOTIFIED THE DOW E/R TEAM WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE CM DISPATCHER THAT THEY WERE ENROUTE TO ASSIST WITH THE LEAK.  AT 1530 HRS., I RICK ZIESEMER ARRIVED AT THE SCENE.  I OBSERVED ONE DROP PER SECOND LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET INTO A PLASTIC BUCKET.  AFTER MY ASSESSMENT, AND AFTER PUTTING ON APPROPRIATE SAFE CLOTHING AND GLOVES, I PROCEEDED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND TIGHTENED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AS TIGHT AS I COULD. WITHIN A FEW MINUTES, THE DRIPPING SLOWED DOWN CONSIDERABLY.  AT APPROX. 1700 HRS., THE DOW E/R TEAM ARRIVED.  THEY REMOVED THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO ALLOW ANY LIQUID THAT HAD COLLECTED TO DISCHARGE.  AFTER A SHORT PERIOD OF OBSERVATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS COATED WITH TEFLON TAPE AND SECURED BACK ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  MINOR REMEDIATION OF THE SITE WAS ACCOMPLISHED BY THE DOW E/R TEAM AND THE TANK WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT AT 1814 HRS. CAR WAS MOVED TO THE DOW CHEMICAL COMPLEX AT MIDLAND ON MARCH 14, 1995.

column168: ON 3/7/95 AT 2355 THE CAPTAIN OF THE INTEGRITY ADVISED TANK SECS543067 LOADED ON BOARD WAS LEAKING.  BRIAN BROWN, MARINE SUPERVISOR, CALLED PAT PARRISH AT 2400 ADVISING TANK LEAKING A THICK, CLEAR RESIDUE.  AT 2405 PAT PARRISH NOTIFIED THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TO SECURE AREA OF LEAKING TANK.  BETWEEN 2405 AND 2425 PAT PARRISH NOTIFIED CHEMTEC, JOE RAZOLAN, REQUESTING TO CONTACT REPRESENTATIVE FROM MATLCK.  PAT PARRISH ADVISED TANK WAS LEAKING, UN NUMBER, CLASS, RESIN SOLUTION.  CHEMTREC PUT ON THE LINE, ED HAYES, 1-800-628-5225 OF MATLACK.  ED WOULD CONTACT ANOTHER REPRESENTATVE TO CALL PAT PARRISH.  PAT THEN CONTACTED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CENTER AND ADVISED OF SITUATION AND NEED TO PROVIDE RESPONSE CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP.  PAT PARRISH NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 2425.  REPORT NUMBER 282412 WAS ASSIGNED.  PAT PARRISH CONTACTED THE SEAL-LAND GUARD TO ADVISE EMERGENCY CREW RESPONDING.  SHE ALSO CALLED MARINE SUPERIVOSR, BRIAN BROWN, TO ADVISE ACTIONS.  BILL HALLORAN OF MATLACK (302) 407-2025 PHONE PAT.  SHE ADVISED HIM OF SITUATION.  HE STATED TO CHECK SAFETY CAP 4 BOLTS, BUTTERFLY VALVE, INTERIOR SAFETY VALVES.  HE VERIFIED PRODUCT IS RESIN SOLUTION, UN1866, 3.2, 50-55F, PKG #, RESPONSE GUIDE #26.  PAT PHONED EMTECH TO RECONFIRM INFORMATION AND RELAY INFORMATION FOR MATLACK.  PAT PARRISH CALLED THE TEXAS LAND COMMISION, REPORT NUMBER 950250 WAS ASSIGNED.  EMTECH RESPONDED.  THEY CLOSED THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF VALVE AND TIED OFF THE EARS ON THE CAP.  THEY WERE NOT SEALED.  THEY ADVISED BUTTERFLY VALVE WAS LEAKING.  EMTECH STOPPED THE LEAK.  CLEANED APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT ON CONCRETE ASPHALT AND CLEANED APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS FROM SHIPS DECK.  NO PRODUCT LEAKED INTO WATER WAY OR DRAINS.  MR. HALLORAN WAS NOTIFIED 3/8/95 OF FINDINGS AND NEED TO PICK TANK UP FOR REPAIR.  LEAK WAS PREVENTABLE.  MATLACK ADVISED TO CLOSE VALVES AND CHECK SEALS.  MR. HALLORAN DID ADVISE TANK WAS PRESSURE TESTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND PASSED TEST.

ON MARCH 11, 1995, I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED TO THE LAST ARRIVING AIRCRAFT TO PICK UP THE HAZ MAT FREIGHT.  THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE CAME OFF TO THE AIRCRAFT AND I OPENED THE DOOR.  THERE WAS A STRONG FLAMMABLE ODOR INSIDE.  TECHNICIAN MCLAUGHLIN DONED AN ORGANIC VAPOR RESPIRATOR AND STRUCTURAL FIRE-FIGHTING EQUIPMENT TO INVESTIGATE THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE.  INSIDE THE UNIT HAD DEVICE WAS FIBERBOARD BOX MARKED "RESIN SOLUTION, #UN1866, LTD. QTY."  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE INNER CONTENTS WE FOUND A GLASS RECEPTACLE THAT WAS BROKEN, ALLOWING ITS CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THIS GLASS RECEPTICLE HAS CAPACITY OF 3 OUNCES.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO ITS DESTINATION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON MARCH 11, 1995, SORT SUPERVISOR, ANDY HOLMES REPORTED A SHIPMENT IN THE MAIN SORT LEAKING.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, JEFF MCLAUGHLIN RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, WE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX.  UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX WE FOUND TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE METAL RECEPTACLES.  EACH INNER FIBERBOX CONTAINED 24 METAL RECEPTACLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES.  ON THE LABEL OF THE METAL RECEPTICLES WAS "ISOPROPYL ALCOHOL, FLAMMABLE LIQUID."  THESE TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE LOADED AGAINST PROPER ORIENTATION.  THIS SHIPMENT DID HAVE "ORM-D" CONSUMER COMMODITY MARKINGS ON THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX. THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING FOR AIR TRANSPORT.  THIS SHIPMENT IS HELD AT HAZ MAT SORT AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON 3-8-95 SORT SUPERVISOR, LEE BROOKS REPORTED A SHIPMENT LEAKING AND EMITING AN ODOR. I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIAN, KEN HAAG INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE TECHNICIAN HAAG DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX. INSIDE WERE TWO, ONE QUART CAPACITY RECEPTACLES.  ONE WAS METAL AND THE OTHER WAS PLASTIC.  THESE BOTH HAD SCREW TYPE CLOSURE WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  THE METAL RECEPTACLE LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURE.  ALSO INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS OTHER MISC.  CAMPING EQUIPMENT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

I RESPONDED TO THE WEST CENTER SLIDE, USED THE DECISION TREE, WORE BOOTS, GLOVES, APRON. AND GOGGLES.  IDENTIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS PACKAGE BY THE FIVE PART FORM.  USED CORROSIVE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  INITIAL PH TEST RESULTED WITH A READING OF 12 PH.  USED SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE SPILL, FINAL PH READING WAS 7PH.  ABSORBED LIQUID WITH FLOOR DRI AND THE CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

ON MARCH 9,1995, AT 01:56, RAMP LEAD DEE REINE REPORTED A SPILL WITH AN ODOR.  THE SPILL WAS LOCATED ON THE GROUND AT "B" RAMP BY BELLY ONE OF AN AB AIRCRAFT.  THIS AIRCRAFT WAS LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNT DR., WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  HAZMAT COORDINATOR ADDIE CAMPTON AND SPILL TECHNICIANS RANDY WILLIAMS AND MARK GRIFFITH RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, WE TOOK PROPER PRECAUTIONS AND DONNED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATIONS, WE FOUND A 5 GALLON PLASTIC JERRI CAN THAT CONTAINED A FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  SPILL TECHNICIAN RANDY WILLIAMS INSPECTED THE SHIPMENT AND FOUND THE CLOSURE OF THE JERRI AN TO HAVE A FAULTY CLOSURE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AS THE FOLLOWING DANGEROUS GOODS:  THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME WAS "EXTRACTS, FLAVORING LIQUID 3, UN1197 PG. II.  THE CORRECT CERTIFICATION WAS PREPARED IATA AND THE CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS ONE OF A SIX PIECE SHIPMENT, BUT, ONLY ONE (1) PIECE LEAKED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED IN PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE:  JOSEPH VICTORI WINES, INC. THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS FAULTY CLOSURE.  WE WERE CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 02:09.

ON 3/16/95 AT 0150, MARY LATHRAM, HAZ MAT SORT LEAD, REPORTED A LIQUID SPILL WITH AN ODOR AT THE HAZMAT SORT AREA FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DR., WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORD., ADDIE CAMPTON, AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS RANDY WILLIAMS AND TAMMY FLORENCE RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON OUR ARRIVAL WE RECEIVED INFORMATION THAT HIS SHIPMENT WAS A POISON.  AFTER SECURING THE AREA AND TAKING ALL THE NECESSARY PRECAUTIONS, WE BEGAN OUR INVESTIGATION.  UPON INSPECTION OF THIS SHIPMENT, THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS FOUND TO BE WET, NO P-H READING, AND THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE BOX CONTAINED SIX (6) GLASS ONE (1) LITRE BOTTLES EACH OF CHLOROFORM, 6.1 POISONOUS MATERIAL, UN1888 PG. III. ONE OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES WAS FOUND TO HAVE HAD A VACUUM SEAL CLOSURE WHICH HAD FAILED.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR FAILURE WAS POSSIBLE OVERFILLING OF THE RECEPTACLES.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND (IATA) DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER UPON REQUEST.  THERE WERE NO OTHER PACKAGES INVOLVED, BUT WE DID HAVE THREE 93) EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR, BUT RECEIVED NO MEDICAL ATTENTION.  WE WERE CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 0300.

column168: ON 3/16/95 AT 0037, BILL MCEVOY, RAMP LOADER, REPORTED A SPILL AT AN ABX AIRCRAFT ON B RAMP, LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC.  145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COORD, ADDIE CAMPTON, AND P/T SPILL TECHNICIAN, RANDY WILLIAMS RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL WE FOUND A WET FIBREBOARD BOX BY BELLY FOUR (4) OF THE AIRCRAFT. THERE WAS ONLY PAPER PACKING MATERIAL AROUND THE RECEPTACLES USED AS CUSHIONING AND NO ABSORBENT WAS USED.  THE OUTER BOX WAS JUST DAMP.  THIS OUTER BOX WAS JUST DAMP.  THIS OUTER PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AS AN (IATA) DANGEROUS GOODS, AND THE PROPER (IATA) DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS DID ACCOMPANY THIS PKG.  THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION WAS MARKED ON THE CERTIFICATION AND THE PACKAGE:  "CONSUMER COMMODITY, CLASS 9, ID 8000".  THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM, AND ALL PROPER MARKINGS, AND LABELS APPLIED, AND THE SHIPMENT RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  BECAUSE WE DO NOT FORWARD LEAKING SHIPMENTS OUT OF THE UNITED STATES.  WE WERE CLEAR OF THE SCENE AT 0057.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A TO A CONVENIENCE STORE'S UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  THERE ARE TWO UNLEADED TANKS MANIFOLDED TOGETHER.  AS THE GAS BEING UNLOADED INTO TANK I REACHED 56", THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM'S OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM BLOCKED OFF THE VENT LINE. THIS CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD IN THE SECOND TANK'S VENT SYSTEM PRODUCING A SMALL SPRAY OF GAS OUT OF THE VENT FITTING.  SPILL CONFINED ON BLACKTOP & IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP.  STEWART'S MARKETING HAS BEEN ADVISED TO NOT ORDER A QUANTITY OF GAS THAT WILL ALLOW THE DELIVERED PRODUCT TO REACH 56" IN THE TANK.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL.  CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED ANS ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #94-16722 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: FRA INSPECTOR FAGE TALBERT FOUND A TANK CAR WITH DRIED RESIDUE ON ITS SIDES AT CSTX' RAIL YARD IN MONTGOMERY AL. MECHANICAL TIGHTENED THE BOLTS, ALSO AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: EMPLOYEE J. WATTS WAS DRIVING B.T.#419 HEADING EAST ON N.C. HWY 901.  IT WAS DARK, RAINING AND FOGGY.  ABOUT 3 MILES EAST OF HARMONY, NC., NEAR SHEFFIELD RD. HE ATTEMPTED TO ROUND A CURVE.  ENTERING THE CURVE HE LOST CONTROL AND TRAVELLED A DITCH LINE FOR ABOUT 400 FEET.   AS THE TRUCK SLOWED DOWN, HE STEERED IT NOT A FALLOW FARM FIELD.  AS HE CUT TO THE LEFT THE FRONT WHEELS BOGGED DOWN IN THE SOFT MUD AND THE TRUCK LAID OVER ON THE DRIVER SIDE.  THE DRIVER WAS CITED THE N.C. HIGHWAY PATROL "AT A SPEED GREATER THAT REASONABLE AND PRUDENT TO WIT" "WET CONDITIONS". NOTIFIED: N.C. HWY PATROL, HARMONY VOL. FIRE DEPT., P.E.I. MAINT. DEPT., P.E.I. CLEAN-UP CREW.  SECURED A 35 TON CRANE TO LIFT B.T.419 UPRIGHT, & A LIFT TRUCK WRECKER TO HAUL IT BACK TO P.E.I. MAINT. SHOP.  FERTILIZER WAS SHOVELLED UP INTO 45 GAL. DRUMS & RETURNED TO P.E.I MAGAZIN E.  VOL. FIRE DEPT WASHED MUD OFF HIGHWAY TO THE SATISFACTION OF N.C. HWY DEPT.  RUTS IN FARM FIELD SHALL BE GRADED TO FARMERS' SATISFACTION.  DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO IREDELL MEMORIAL HOSPITAL TO BE EXAMINED FOR INJURIES.  WHILE THERE HE WAS GIVEN A POST ACCIDENT DRUG & ALCOHOL TEST.  BOTH PROVED NEGATIVE.  HWY 901 N.C. NOW OFF LIMITS TO P.E.I. TRUCKS.  NEW ROUTE PLAN WRITTEN EMPLOYING I-77 AND I-40 EFFECTIVE 3/7/95.

column168: TRAILER NUMBER 48-38 WAS SITTING AT THE DOCK AT TTMS IN RICHLAND, MS, ON 3/12/94.  THE TRAILER WAS PULLED OUT TO OPEN THE DOORS AND RETURNED TO THE DOCK FOR UNLOADING.  AT THIS POINT THE DOCKWORKER NOTICED A SMELL AND NOTIFIED JOHN STOMPS.  AT THIS POINT MR. STOMPS CHECKED THE BILL OF LADING AND REFERRED TO THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK FOR PROPER PROCEDURES. THERE WAS ONLY ONE PERSON WORKING ON THE DOCK AND HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO STAY CLEAR OF THE AREA UNTIL TOLD DIFFERENT.  MR. STOMPS THEN CALLED CHEMTREC TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE BEFORE PROCEEDING.  AFTER DISCUSSION WITH DENNIS LEE ON SUNDAY OF SPECIALTY PRODUCTS, MR. STOMPS WAS ADVISED TO FIND THE LEAK IF POSSIBLE AND ISOLATE IT FROM WORK AREA.  THE 60 CYLINDER TO BE LEAKING SLOWLY.  HE THEN TRANSPORTED THE ENTIRE SKID TO AN OPEN AREA FOR THE GAS TO DISSIPATE.  THE PRODUCT WAS KEPT ISOLATED UNTIL A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE MANUFACTURER COULD INSPECT.  KEN CUEVAS, MANUFACTURER'S REPRESENTATIVE OF GULF STATES AIRGAS ARRIVED 3/14/95.  HE DETERMINED THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A FAULTY PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE.  THE CYLINDER WAS EMPTY UPON HIS INSPECTION.  MR. CUEVAS STATED THAT BY ISOLATION IN AN OPEN AREA FOR DISSIPATION OF THE GAS THERE WAS AND IS NOT NOW ANY ENVIRONMENTAL OR HEALTH HAZARD.  THE CYLINDER WAS MARKED AS HAVING FAULTY VALVE AND NOT TO BE REFILLED.  RECOMMENDATION FOR PREVENTION OF FUTURE INSTANCES IS THAT ALL REFILLABLE CYLINDERS BE THOROUGHLY CHECKED ON A PERIODIC BASIS AND CERTIFIED FOR USE.

ON MARCH 9,1995 WE HAD MINOR OIL SPILL AT THE DWAYNE BAER RESIDENCE, BERLINE TWP., WAYNE CO. PA.  MY DRIVER SAID THAT THE OIL BLEW BACK OUT OF THE VENT PIPE AND HE PROCEEDED TO SHUT IT DOWN IMMEDIATELY.  UPON MY NOTIFICATIONS, WHICH WAS NOT UNTIL 3/15/95, I CONTACTED THE EPA, US DER, PA. DER, WAYNE COUNTY HAZARDOUS RESPONSE & S&M ENVIRONMENTAL CO. IN MILFORD, PIKE CO. PA.  ON 3/17/95 S&M ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSED THE SPILL & EXCAVATED APPROXIMATELY 20 TON OF CONTAMINATED SOIL, PUTTING IT ON 6 MIL POLY LINERS.  THE DIRT WAS THEN COVERED WITH THE SAME 6 MIL POLY LINERS. AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, THE TANK WAS PUMPED, REMOVED & I HAVE OFFERED TO INSTALL A NEW TANK.  THE EXCAVATION PROCESS WAS CONCLUDED WHEN IT WAS DETERMINED BY ONE F S&M'S TRAINED SUPERVISORS THAT THERE WAS NO EXISTING CONTAMINATION.  FIVE (5) SOIL SAMPLES AND TWO (2) WATER SAMPLES WERE TAKEN BY S&M AND SENT TO A CERTIFIED LABORATORY.  THE RESULTS CAME BACK "NEGATIVE" WITH THE EXCEPTION OF A VERY SMALL READING IN ONE OF THE SAMPLES

column168: DATE: MARCH 22, 1995 TERMINAL: HEARNE LOCATION: HWY 190 & 93 EAST OF TEMPLE, BELL COUNTY TEXAS. BACKGROUND: AT 7:36 AM CTCO DRIVER LEFT THE EXXON LOADING RACK AT HEARNE, TEXAS AND PROCEEDED TO FORD HOOD, AT KILLEEN, TEXAS. AT THE INTERSECTION OF HWY 190 & 93 AT 8:30 AM, THE DRIVER ATEMPTED TO MAKE A TURN AND ROLLED THE TRUCK INTO THE DITCH ALONGSIDE THE HIGHWAY. REPORT: AT 8:45 AM THE EXXON HOUSTON DISPATCHER NOTIFIED THE HEARNE TERMINAL AND ADVISED TERMINAL MANAGER ZIL HARLAN OF THE INCIDENT, AND ALSO REPORTED THAT THE DRIVER WAS INJURED. RESPONSE: MR. HARLAN IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED THE TERMINAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRAILER AND CREW TO THE SCENE, AND NOTIFIED AN EMPTY TRUCK AT FORD HOOD TO PROCEED DIRECTLY TO THE INCIDENT SITE. IN ADDITION MR. HARLAN NOTIFIED THE CTCO CORPORATE OFFICE IN SAN ANTONIO AND THE SAFETY DIRECTOR IN PHOENIX, AZ. THE SAFETY DIRECTOR IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY REPONSE TEAM FROM EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES IN FT. WORTH AND A VACUUM TRUCK FROM MOBLEY IN AUSTIN. THE SAFETY DIRECTOR ADDITIONALLY WAS ABLE TO MAKE CONTACT WITH THE FIRE CHIEF AT THE LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT. THE CHIEF ADVISED THE DRIVER HAD A CUT OVER ONE EYE AND THAT APPEARED TO BE THE EXTENT OF INJURIES. HOWEVER THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS ON ITS SIDE AND THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. THE SAFETY DIRECTOR AUTHORIZED THE FIRE CHIEF TO HIRE A LOCAL FRONT END LOADER AT CTCO EXPENSE, TO BLOCK THE DITCH AT EITHER END OF THE TRUCK TO PREVENT ADDITIONAL CONTAMINATION. THE CHEIF ADVISED THAT ACTION WOULD BE TAKEN IMMEDIATELY. THE FIRE CHIEF WAS ADVISED THAT EMTECH WAS EN-ROUTE, AND THAT THEY SHOULD TAKE NO ACTION OTHER THAN CONTAINMENT, IN AN EFFORT TO PREVENT FURTHER INJURIES TO EITHER FIRE FIGHTERS OR THE PUBLIC. THE FIRE CHIEF ADVISED EVERYTHING WAS UNDER CONTROL AND THEY WOULD WAIT FOR EMTECH TO ARRIVE. ADDITIONAL MANAGEMENT TEAM MEMBERS TONY CULPEPPER, OPERATIONS SUPERVISOR, PHIL EDWARDS, FLEET DIRECTOR, AND CLYDE CROW, HOUSTON TERMINAL MANAGER AND OSHA 1910.120 CERTIFIED, WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE. EMTECH RESPONSE MANAGER CHIP DAY WAS CONTACTED BY THE SAFETY DIRECTOR AND PROVIDED WITH AN UPDATE FROM THE SCENE, AND THE PHONE NUMBER AT THE COMMAND POST SO THAT HE COULD CONTACT THE FIRE CHIEF DIRECTLY. CONDITIONS DESCRIBED TO THE SAFETY DIRECTOR BY THE FIRE CHIEF INDICATED THE BEST PROCEDURE WOULD BE TO DRILL EACH COMPARTMENT OF THE BEST PROCEDURE WOULD BE TO DRILL EACH COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK USING THE SHELL METHOD, TO OFF LOAD THE PRODUCT. THIS PROCEDURE WAS AUTHORIZED BY COASTAL AND THE PROCEDURE WAS COMPLETED BY EMTECH. TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT BEGAN WITHIN TWENTY (20) MINUTES OF THEIR ARRIVAL ON SITE. THE VACUUM TRUCK BEGAN PICKING UP SPILLED PRODUCT AND FIRE FIGHTING FOAM UPON ITS ARRIVAL. AT 2:00 PM THE OVER TURNED TRUCK WAS EMPTIED, AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE. AN ENVIRONMENTAL ASSESSMENT WAS COMPLETED BY EMTECH FOLLOWING THE RECOVERY OF 3,020 GALLONS FREE FLOATING GASOLINE, FIRE FIGHTING FOAM AND WATER, THIS VOLUME INCLUDED 732 GALLONS OF GASOLINE LOST.

column168: MANITO TRANSIT WAS INSTRUCTED TO DELIVER 2000 GAL. OF GASOLINE TO KAVANICK'S STATION AT ADDRESS ABOVE BY MILLER OIL CO. OF CHAMPAIGN, 11. AT 3:00 P.M. ON 3-27-95 THE MANITO TRANSPORT ENTERED STATION PROPERTY. MANITO DRIVER TIMOTY JONES, BEGAN THE DELIVERY PROCESS BY 1ST GAUGING THE TANKS AS PER CUSTOMER DELIVERY INSTRUCTIONS. MR. JONES THEN SECURED DELIVERY HOSE AND PROPER DELIVERY ELBOW (MCDONELL-DOUGLAS TIGHT-FILL) AND BEGAN PRODUCT FLOW. AFTER A FEW MOMENTS THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPRAY OUT OF CUSTOMER FILL-PIPE. MR. JONES THEN CLOSED ALL VALVES AT TRANSPORT, BUT BACK PRESSURE IN CUSTOMER TANK CAUSED A GEYSER EFFECT AND SPRAYED A 12' X 20' AREA WITH GASOLINE. CUSTOMER VENT SYSTEM NOT OPERATING PROPERLY. THE WESTVILLE, IL. FIRE DEPT. WAS DISPATCHED FOR SAFETY REASONS AND MR. JONES USED "SPILL RAG" TO SOAK ANY STANDING PUDDLES ON DRIVE AREA. ONCE AREA SECURED MR. JONES CALLED MANITO OFFICE TO REPORT INCIDENT TO LEE LOURET (TERMINAL MANAGER). WE THEN DISPATCHED A PICK-UP TRUCK TO THE SCENE WITH ADDITIONAL SOAK-UP RAGS, BOOMS, AND OIL DRY. DRIVE AREA CLEAN-UP WAS SATISFACTORY TO FIRE DEPT. AND THEN E.S.D.A. DIRECTOR EDWARD E. MILLER. MR. JONES THEN COMPLETED DELIVERY AND LEFT STATION PROPERTY. AMOUNT OF RELEASE HAS YET TO BE DETERMINED AT THIS TIME, BUT APPEARS TO BE 20 TO 30 GALLONS OR LESS.

column168: DRIVER PUNCTURED DRUM WITH A NAIL WHILE UNLOADING.

DSR DAVE TOTON NOTICED THE PUNCTURED DRUM AT HIS 1ST DELIVERY AFTER HE HAD PICKED UP THE 4 DRUMS FROM SHEFFIELD PRODUCTS.  DAVE HAD PICKED-UP 4 DRUMS ON ONE SKID, BLOCKED THEM IN WITH PLYWOOD AND OTHER FREIGHT AROUND THEM. THE FREIGHT IN FRONT OF THE DRUMS WAS BLOCKED IN WITH A LOAD BAR WHICH FAILED AND ALLOWED A PIECE OF MACHINERY TO MOVE FORWARD IN TRANSIT.  THE DRUMS SHIFTED ENOUGH TO ALLOW ONE TO FALL FORWARD AGAINST THE MACHINERY, PUNCTURING ONE OF THE FOUR DRUMS ON THE SKID.  DAVE CALLED DAN JONES WHO CALLED CHEMTREC, WHO CALLED THE SHIPPER, WHO IN TURN ADVISED US TO PUT ABSORBANT ON THE SPILL.  ART BIRDSALL, THE CONTACT AT SHEFFIELD, ALSO ADVISED US TO PUT THE DRUM AND ABSORBANT IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THEY WOULD DISPOSE OF IT PROPERLY WITH THEIR REGULAR WASTE.  EXTRA ATTENTION HAS BEEN, AND WILL BE GIVEN WHEN HANDLING ANY HAZMAT, TO ENSURE THIS TYPE OF SITUATION DOES NOT TAKE PLACE DUE TO NEGIGENCE.

HE NOTICED A TERRIBLE ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER,  THE SUPERVISOR, MIKE WOODDY CALLED ME TO THE 172 DOOR.  I NOTICED A LIQUID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  JOE MOVED SOME SKIDS AND FOUND (1) 35 GALLON DRUM LEAKING.  (UN2922 II), CORROSIVE LIQUID/POISONOUS NOS.  I THEN HAD JOE PUT DOWN SOME QUICK-SORB TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  WE PULLED THAT TRAILER AWAY FROM THE DOCK AND CONTRACTED CONSOLIDATED WASTE, INDUSTRIES. CONSOLIDATED SHOWED UP AND TOOK CARE OF THE SPILL.

column168: THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF A SINGLE VEHICLE TRAFFIC ACCIDENT WHEN THE TRAILER OF A COMBINATION TANK TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE IMPACT AND SUBSEQUENT SLIDING OVER THE CONCRETE PAVEMENT RESULTED IN CARGO TANK FAILURE WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 2660 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT HAS BEEN DETERMINED TO BE DRIVER ERROR.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO CONTAIN MIXTURE OF RAINWATER AND GASOLINE UNTIL A LOCAL SPILL CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR COULD RESPOND WITH PROPER CLEANUP EQUIPMENT.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP WITH SORBENT MATERIALS AND VACUUM TRUCKS AND TRANSPORTED TO A LOCAL PROCESSING AND DISPOSAL CONTRACTOR FOR PROPER HANDLING OF THE PRODUCT AND RAIN WATER MIXTURE.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF DRIVER ERROR, DISCIPLINARY ACTION HAD BEEN TAKEN AGAINST THE DRIVER.

column168: ON MARCH 13TH,1995, STEVE MANTZ, OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO KRUEGER INTERNATIONAL IN GILLETT, WI TO MAKE A DELIVERY.  ON HWY 29-32 WEST, JUST AFTER EXITING HWY 41 NORTH, THE DRIVER WAS CUT OFF IN TRAFFIC AND HAD TO BRAKE HARD TO AVOID AN ACCIDENT.  THE RESULT OF THIS ACTION WAS THE SHIFTING OF FREIGHT INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THREE OF FOUR TOTE CONTAINERS, SEPARATED FROM THEIR SKIDS CAUSING ONE OF THE TOTES TO RUPTURE.  THE DRIVER WAS FLAGGED DOWN BY A PASSING MOTORIST.  HE STOPPED HIS VEHICLE IN AN AREA AWAY FROM MAJOR TRAFFIC AND DWELLINGS, ABOUT 1 1/2 MILES AWAY. LOCAL D.N.R. OFFICIAL AND A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAN UP CREW WERE CALLED WITH TO THE SCENE.  THE SPILL WAS PRIMARILY CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER WITH SOME MATERIAL LEAKING TO THE GROUND THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR BOARDS. THIS MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA BY BUILDING UP DIRT AROUND THAT AREA.  THE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER WAS COLLECTED AND PUT INTO 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  WHEN THE CLEAN UP AT THE SCENE WAS FINISHED, THE TRAILER WAS TAKEN TO KRUEGER INTERNATIONALS GREEN BAY PLANT FOR A FEW DAYS UNTIL THE FUMES FROM THE SPILL DISSIPATED AND A CREW COULD ENTER THE TRAILER AND SECURE THE REMAINING FULL TOTES.  THIS WAS ACCOMPLISHED ON MARCH 17TH.  THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO WEST BEND WHERE THE REMAINING MATERIAL WAS CLEANED OUT.  THEN THE REMAINING GOOD  MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO THE COOK COMPOSITES & POLYMERS SAUKVILLE PLANT ON MARCH 20TH FOR SALVAGE.  OUR INVESTIGATION AS TO WHY THE LOAD SHIFTED PROVED TO BE IMPROPER LOADING AND SECURING OF FREIGHT.  THE TOTES WERE ONLY SECURED AT THE REAR AND SINCE THE TOTES WERE NOT IN THE NOSE OF TRAILER, THE MATERIAL IN FRONT OF TOTES WAS NOT ABLE TO PREVENT THE TOTES FROM SHIFTING OFF OF THEIR SKIDS WHEN THE DRIVER HAD TO BRAKE HARD.  WE HAVE TALKED TO OUR PEOPLE ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPER LOADING AND REMINDED THEM OF THEIR PREVIOUS TRAINING WHICH INCLUDED THE PROPER SECUREMENT OF FREIGHT.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN PRIMARY SORT.  WHEN OPENED IT WAS FOUND THAT IT WAS A PUMP LEAKING GASOLINE.  THE PUMP WAS DRAINED, REPACKAGED, AND SENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED CARTON AND THE PORTION THAT LEAKED WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ADDITIONAL COMMENTS:  ON 03-24-95 A SPILL WAS REPORTED BY SORT SUPERVISOR HAROLD CRITES IN "D" BUILDING SORT FACILITY AT ABX, IN., 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS MARK GRIFFTH AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON THEIR INVESTIGATION THEY DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND TESTING THEY DISCOVERED THAT THIS PACKAGE WAS CLEARLY A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED NO ABSORBENT OR OTHER MARKINGS ON THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX INDICATING THIS WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE A 12 VOLT BATTERY FILLED WITH ACID WHICH IS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT IN A SPECIFICATION PACKAGE.  PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT AND THE CORRECT MARKINGS AND LABELS WERE NOT APPLIED.  THE TERMINAL WERE PROTECTED WITH BLACK ELECTRICAL TAPE.  THE ONLY THEORY FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS THAT IT WAS NOT IN A SPECIFICATION PACK AND IT WAS NOT PACKAGED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ON BELT.  1 OF 10 BOTTLES WAS LEAKING. PROCESSED THRU DMP.

THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL OCCURED AT 18:25 IN BAY 83.  JAMES LENNON FOUND THE PACKAGE & NOTIFIED SANTO SCUPERO.   SANTO RESPONDED BY FIRST REFERING TO THE DECISION TREE, THEN FOLLOWING RESPONSE SHEET ON A FLAMMABLE LIQUID. PPE SANTO USED AN APRON, GLOVES, GOGGLES.  BOOTS NOT NECESSARY DUE TO LACK OF SPILLAGE & SCBA WAS NOT NECESSARY DUE TO LACK OF ODOR.  SOLUSORB WAS USED ON THE PACKAGE TO REDUCE FLAMMABILITY.  PLACED INTO TWO DMP BAGS.

PACKAGE WAS LEAKING IN TRAILER #297317.  IT HAD NO INDICATION ON THE BOX THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED USING P.P.E. IN A DMP BAG.  ON TESTING THE PH LEVEL OF THE PACKAGE.  IT HAD A PH 0 WHICH IS A STRONG ACID.  PACKAGE WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER WITH A "NOTIFICATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REPORT."  CAP WAS TIGHTENED AND SHIPMENT RETURNED. CONTAMINATED MATERIALS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMP PROCEDURES.  A LOADER HAD TOUCH MATERIAL AND WAS INSTRUCTED TO WASH HIS HANDS FOR 15 MIN.  HIS HANDS WERE FINE AND NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.

0705:  I RESPONDED TO PD2, DOOR 156, TRAILER 82232 TO FIND A BOX WITH WET SPOTS, *BOX WAS LABELED WITH PAINT STICKER ON SIDE ON 5 PT THAT SAID PAINT/UN1263, ETC. I OPENED THE BOX TO FIND A PLASTIC JUG, I TESTED IT AND GOT A READING OF O PH.  I CONSULTED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET (LIQUID CORROSIVE).  DONNED MY PPE AND REMOVED BOX TO DAMAGE CAGE, NEUTRALIZED THE (PHOS.ACID) WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND PROCESSED PACKAGE IN ACCORDING WITH UPS HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROGRAM. column168: AT 1800 HOURS A DERAILMENT OCCURED AT NORTH END OF TEN TRACK IN NORTH LITTLE ROCK HUMP YARD, INVOLVED IN DERAILMENT WAS TANK CAR ECUX 102214 WHICH CONSISTED OF TWO SEPERATE TANKS COMPARTMENTS 1 AND 2.  SWITCH CREWS OBSERVED LIQUID COMING FROM COMPARTMENT 1.  BOTH COMPARTMENTS WERE ON THEIR SIDES.  NORTH LITTLE ROCK YARD MASTER NOTIFIED MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORATION SAFETY C. HILL WHO ARRIVED AT 1840 HOURS.  HIS INSPECTION REVEALED COMPARTMENT 1  CONTAINED NAPHTHA WHICH WAS LEAKING FROM MANWAY. SPILL WAS CONTAINED AFTER TIGHTENING LOOSE MANWAY COVER BOLTS. COMPARTMENT 2 CONTAINING METHYL ETHYL KETONE NEVER LEAKED.  LOSS OF NAPHTHA WAS ESTIMATED AT 300 GALLONS, WHICH WAS REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED BY HARRIMAN DISPATCH CENTER.  CONTACT WAS MADE WITH SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE WILLARD BEARD.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH MR. BEARD TO TRANSLOAD BOTH COMPARTMENTS INTO TANK TRUCKS ON FRIDAY, APRIL 7, 1995.

column168: UPRR MTO KEITH NORRIS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR CHVX 287202 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM FITTING. CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE YARD AT MONAHANS, TX., READY TO INTERCHANGE TO THE T&NM RR WHEN THE LEAK WAS NOTED BY UPRR TRAINMEN. A CONTAINER WAS PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CATCH SPILLED PRODUCT AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE GASKET OR SEAL AROUND THE BOTTOM VALVE HANDLE. ALL ATTEMPTS TO TIGHTEN THE FITTING AND STOP THE LEAK FAILED. CHEVRON AND CHEM CENTRAL, THEY ARRANGED FOR THE CAR TO BE OFFLOADED INTO TRUCKS. THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED BY 2100 HRS. THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT COLLECTED, EVAPORATED WITHIN MINUTES. TNRCC WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED THAT NO CLEANUP WAS NEEDED. THEY CONCURRED. ONCE OFFLOADED CHVX 287202 TRAVELED TO FORT WORTH, TX. WHERE IT WAS STENCILLED LEAKY TANK. DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPARIED" AND SENT TO REPAIR FACILITY.

UPRR MTO JERRY WHITE REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 201121 WAS LEAKING LIQUID FROM BOTH SAFETY VALVES. CAR WAS LOCATED AT RAY YARD, DENNIS, TX. UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND THE REPORT ACCURATE AND DETERMINED THE CAR WAS OVERFULL BECAUSE OF PRODUCT EXPANSION. THE CAR HAD BEEN LOADED IN MICHIGAN AND THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE IN DENNIS, TX. WAS IN THE LOW 80'S. BY 1900 HOURS THE CAR COOLED SUFFICIENTLY TO STOP THE SPILLAGE. THE SPILLAGE EVAPORATED BEFORE CONTACTING THE GROUND. MS. ROQUET CONTACTED MELANIE KELLEY OF TOTAL PETROLEUM (303-291-2042) WHO ARRANGED FOR A PETRO-CHEMICAL TANK TRUCK TO OFFLOAD PRODUCT AT 0700 HOURS, 3-24-95. THE CAR WAS SO FULL THAT THE LIQUID LINE WAS HOOKED UP, VALVE WAS OPENED, AND AS THE TRUCK PUMP STARTED PULLING, THE AIR VALVE WAS OPENED, IN ORDER TO LOWER PRODUCT LEVEL AND OPEN MANWAY. PRODUCT WAS STILL 1-2" UP ON THE MANWAY NOZZLE. THE REST OF THE OFFLOADING WAS DONE THROUGH THE MANWAY AND COMPLETED AT 0940 HRS. A TOTAL OF 1500 GALLONS WAS TAKEN OFF, GIVING APPROXIMATELY 8" OF OUTAGE WHEN DONE. SEALS UPB 203019 AND 203022 WERE APPLIED TO SECURE THE CAR CHEMTREC REPORT #34470.

column168: JAMES W. WAS READY TO TAKE THE PACKAGE FROM THE BELT, WHEN HE LIFTED IT AND THE BOTTOM FELL OUT.  MARK WEIGERT SAW THIS HAPPEN AND THEY BOTH NOTICED IT WAS HAZARDOUS AND EVACUATED THE AREA.  KELLY KRAMER, THE TWELVE HOUR RESPONDER, WENT TO THE SCENE WEARING BOOTS, GLOVES, APRON, MASK AND GOGGLES.  WITH THE EMERGENCY BOOK, IT WAS DECIDED UPON WHAT TO DO NEXT. THE OVERHEAD DOORS WERE OPENED TO AIR THE PLACE OUT.  SOLUSORB WAS USED TO SOAK UP THE LEFTOVER LIQUID.  WHEN AIR HIT THE LIQUID, MOST OF IT EVAPORATED.  THE SOLUSORB AND GLASS WERE SWEPT INTO A DAMAGE CONTAINER. THE OPEN BOX AND DAMAGED BUCKET WERE MOVED OUTSIDE TO FRESH AIR.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND THE PROPER PAPERWORK WAS FILLED OUT.  AFTER EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED UP, THE PRELOAD WAS BROUGHT BACK INTO THE BUILDING AND THE OPERATION WAS FINISHED.  SOME OVERHEAD DOORS WERE LEFT OPEN TO BE SURE THE AREA WAS WELL VENTILATED.  IT APPEARS THAT THE GLUE ON THE SEAM OF THE BOX FAILED.  WHEN THE PRELOADER BEGAN TO LOAD IT, THE BOTTOM SPLIT OPEN AND ONE GLASS JAR FELL TO THE FLOOR AND BROKE.  JAMES WEISENBERGER WAS SENT TO THE HOSPITAL TO BE EXAMINED.  IT APPEARED HE WAS OK.

ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED, DENNY BASKERVILL NOTICED THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE WAS WET AND NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR DARIN MANTERNACH, DARIN SECURED THE AREA AROUND THE PACKAGE AND NOTIFIED DESIGNATED RESPONDER, PAM FOR CLEANUP. PAM RESPONDED WEARING FULL PPE AND FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND THE DAMAGED PACKAGE PROCEDURE FOR UNLABELED PACKAGES. SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO PACKAGE. USED PH TAPE TO IDENTIFY THE DAMAGED PACKAGE AS A CORROSIVE SUBSTANCE. SPILL WAS NEUTRALIZED BY USING SODIUM BICARBONATE AND ABSORBED USING SOLUSORB. UNTIL THE PH READING REACHED 7. SPILL AND PACKAGING WAS PLACED IN THE DMP. ALL PPE WAS DECONTAMINATED.

LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN SECTION TWO.  ONE OF THREE GLASS BOTTLES WAS CRACKED DUE TO POOR PACKAGING.  THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS DISPOSED OF USING PROPER HAZARDOUS DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  DIR #0298167.

column168: OUTSIDE OF BOX COVERED WITH ADHESIVE. MOST PACKAGE MARKINGS ILLEGIBLE. JOHN COSGROVE DISCOVERED THE LEAKING PACKING. HE LEFT THE AREA, AND CONTACTED ME. I INSTRUCTED HIM TO WASH HIS HANDS. THE PACKAGE WAS LABELED AS A "STORE AWAY FROM FOOD" HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. AFTER REFERRING TO THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS, I PUT ON PPE (GLOVE, GOGGLES, APRON), PUT THE PACKAGE INTO A SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT IT TO THE DMP AREA. THE PACKAGE AND ITS CONTENTS WERE BOTH DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO UPS DMP PROCEDURE. AWAITING RESPONSE FROM MALLINHARDT DISPOSAL SERVICE.

DISCOVERED IN METRO LAND SHUT BELT DOWN CLEARED PEOPLE DAWNED PPE REMOVED PACKAGE FROM BELT AND PLACED IN SPILL TUB.  MOVED PACKAGE FROM LOAD AREA.
